An interesting thing about Cambodia which was a neutral country. I remember hearing on the PBS Documentary about Vietnam. In Cambodia, at the time of the war, a large majority (upwards of 80%?) of the people in that country owned their own land. How much of a communist &quot;hotbed&quot; was the Cambodian nation?<br><br>
I wonder how much of a foothold the communists would have gotten had the war not spilled over into their country? Prince Sihanouk was very popular with his people. He was revered. Historically Marxism has taken hold in countries where only a few people own most of the land. The Cambodian people didn't have that problem.<br><br>
The Diem government did nothing to address the land reform problem, while the Viet Cong made it (land reform) one of their primary recruiting tools.<br><br>

